<text>Lac: Local Area Counter

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

The lac command counts atoms of the specified types in a specified rectangular area. The data are shown as a function of time, if there are frames in the recorder. (To see how to count atoms for each individual frame without using scripts, see this section.)

Syntax:

lac [expression]
lac [expression1] and [expression2] and ...... and [expression_n]

The expression can use the within clause that is also used in the select command:

   [id] within ([x], [y], [w], [h])
   [id1]-[id2] within ([x], [y], [w], [h])
   [id1] [id2] ...... [idn] within ([x], [y], [w], [h])

These three clauses can be used to count all atoms of the element type specified by [id], or a range [id1]-[id2], or several element types, that fall within the specified rectangular area. The within keyword followed by a quadruple enclosed in a pair of parentheses is used to specify a rectangular area, with the four numbers (in angstrom) representing the x coordinate and y coordinate of the upper left corner, and the width and the height of the rectangular area, respectively.

 
Element IDs: The ID numbers for elements are defined as follows: Nt: 0; Pl: 1; Ws: 2; Ck: 3. For IDs of the non-editable elements, see this list.
 

If there are no data recorded, the counting will be based on the current coordinates of the atoms and the result will be shown in a popup window. If there are data recorded, each frame will be counted and the results will be shown as a time series in a graph.

 
Caution: You should generally use this command once per script execution. Avoid using it within a loop.
 

 
  
&#12304;This is an embedded model container.&#12305;

The above simulation shows the inter-diffusion of two pure substances into each other&apos;s original territory. Note that the green particles enter into the left area more quickly than the white ones into the right area. The reason can be attributed to a pressure or temperature difference --- the green particles initially have a higher pressure and temperature than the white ones.

